[4] India (dysentery)
Date: Wed 7 Apr 2004
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: New Kerala.com [edited]
<http://www.newkerala.com/news-daily/news/features.php?
action=fullnews&showcomments=1&id=9111>

Dysentery claims 5 lives in Gorakhpur
-------------------------------------
At least 5 children have died in the last 2 days [5-6 Apr 2004] in
Gorakhpur as hospitals reported an alarming rise in the number of dysentery
cases. Dozens more are seriously ill, and hospitals are overflowing with
more and more children being brought in everyday.
A common ailment, the disease has taken on serious proportions due to a
severe heat wave which has led to a water shortage that has forced villagers
to draw water from untreated sources like rivulets. Worried parents have
traveled hundreds of kilometers to Gorakhpur to get their children treated.
"The epidemic started 3 or 4 days back, and we expect more patients. If
primary aid is given to them, then they can be saved. 5 children have died.
Each day, 10-15 children are being admitted to the OPD [Out-Patient
Department]," R.K Gupta, junior doctor at the city's main medical college,
said. State authorities say all efforts are being taken to prevent the
epidemic from spreading.
